<TITLE> British Airways raises fuel surcharges from Nov 15 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Nov 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British Airways Plc said on Monday it was raising its fuel surcharge on tickets booked from Thursday by up to 15 pounds ($31) per flight, after the price of a barrel of oil rose above $90 in recent days. "The decision reflects new record oil prices and takes into account rising fuel costs," BA said in a statement, adding oil has risen by more than $20 per barrel since it last raised its fuel surcharge in June. The surcharge for longhaul flights of less than nine hours will rise by 10 pounds per flight to 48 pounds, and for longhaul flights of more than nine hours by 15 pounds to 58 pounds. Shorthaul flight surcharges will rise 2 pounds to 10 pounds. BA shares were up 1.5 percent at 361 pence by 1415 GMT in a flat market. BA also said it expects the cost of fuel to increase by 136 million pounds in its second half, the six months to end-March. BA reintroduced fuel surcharges in May 2004 at a flat rate of 2.50 pounds per flight, or $4 for flights booked outside Britain. They have risen steadily since, although some long-haul surcharges were cut in Janua
